   <titles>
      <title>Direction Angles â€“ Illustration</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Here we illustrate the direction angles of a vector <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math> and the two coordinate axes:</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para align="center">
               <para.body>
                  <media type="image" active="1" inline="0">
                     <img src="ims/DirectionAnglesR2.gif" height="237" width="343">
                        <image.mapping>
                           <area shape="rect" coords="39,209,101,233">
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>
                                       <math>
                                          <latex>\Vect{e}_1 = (1,0)</latex>
                                       </math> is the standard vector in the first coordinate direction.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                           <area shape="rect" coords="3,142,29,191">
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>
                                       <math>
                                          <latex>\Vect{e}_2 = (0,1)</latex>
                                       </math> is the standard vector in the second coordinate direction.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                           <area shape="poly" coords="35,195,199,112,35,21">
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>
                                       <math>
                                          <latex>\omega_2 := \sphericalangle(\Vect{e}_2,\Vect{x})</latex>
                                       </math> is the second direction angle of the vector <math>
                                          <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                                       </math>.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                           <area shape="poly" coords="242,104,48,201,288,201">
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>
                                       <math>
                                          <latex>\omega_1 := \sphericalangle(\Vect{e}_1,\Vect{x})</latex>
                                       </math> is the first direction angle of the vector <math>
                                          <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                                       </math>.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                        </image.mapping>
                     </img>
                  </media>
               </para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>A vector <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math> has two direction angles: the vector <math>
                     <latex>\omega_1</latex>
                  </math> from the first coordinate axis, and the angle <math>
                     <latex>\omega_2</latex>
                  </math> from the second coordinate axis.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </body>
